#Transform data to better fit our purposes
sd$iri_key <- as.factor(sd$iri_key) #Store numbers should be factors
sd$week <- as.factor(sd$week) #Week should be factor as well
sd$promo <- as.factor(sd$promo) #promotion should be factor as well
x <- pd$UPC #store UPC
#Makes the UPC layout match for each data set.
pd$UPC <- x #Draws from stored UPC value

pd$UPC <- pd$UPC %>%
  str_replace_all("-",".") %>% #Replaces - with . to fit sd's style
  str_sub(4,17) #Removes the first 3 characters so that the style is 01. rather than 00.01.
pd$UPC <- as.factor(pd$UPC) #Turn product UPC into a factor to match sales UPC

#Join Datasets
fd <- full_join(sd,pd,by = "UPC", copy = FALSE)#Full join on UPC to get all columns from both tables

6 Detailed EDA

6.1 Questions we are going to try to answer

1.Which brands generate value from Promotion? 2.Which brands generate value from having Ads? 3.Which Ads are the most optimal for each brand? 4.Where is Kelloggs generating their value?

We are going to be using the variable Value as our score for the profitability of each possibility. Value is derived from mean_price * mean_units. This way we can account for both price decreases and unit sold increases from promotions. It will also help us determine if ads are valuable, as more units sold under advertisements is still valuable even if there isn’t a direct sale to the goods.

6.2 Which brands generate value from Promotion?

#Save graph to PromoValue
PromoValue <- (
  fd2 %>% 
    filter(company == "GENERAL MILLS") %>% #filter to just general mills
    
    mutate(promo = ifelse(promo == "0","No","Yes")) %>% #Change promo 0 into No and promo 1 into Yes
    
    group_by(ad,promo,brand) %>% #use ad promo and brand to separate means
    summarise(mean_price = mean(price),mean_units = mean(units), value = (mean_price*mean_units)) %>% #create mean units and price
    ggplot(aes(x = brand, y = value, fill = promo)) + 
    geom_col(position = "dodge") +
    labs(x = "Brand Name", y = "Value Generated", title = "Promotion does not always generate value for General Mills brands", fill = "Promotion") +
  #Add labels to Brands for easier reading and prevention of overlapping
    scale_x_discrete(labels = c("CHEERIOS" = "Cheerios", "CINNAMON TST CR" = "Cinn. Toast", "COCOA PUFFS" = "Cocoa Puffs", "LUCKY CHARMS" = "Lucky Charms", "KIX" = "Kix"))
)

    
#Display Graph
PromoValue

6.2.1 Comments

  • Cheerios, Kix, and Lucky Charms do not benefit from Promotions
    • This is found by using our Value equation to give us a “score” for each option
  • Cinnamon Toast Crunch and Cocoa Puffs do benefit from promotions
    • This could be due to being more less adult-friendly than Cheerios and Kix
      • Although Lucky Charms is also a kid-friendly cereal more than adult-friendly

6.3 Which brands generate value from having Ads?

#Read graph into AdValue
AdValue <- (
  fd2 %>% 
    filter(company == "GENERAL MILLS") %>% #filter to just general mills
    
    #mutate ad to advert to reduce A and B into one, with NONE being No Advert
    mutate(advert = ifelse(ad == "A"|ad == "B", "Advertisement",
                         ifelse(ad == "NONE", "No Advertisement", "null"))) %>% 
    
    group_by(advert,promo,brand) %>% #use ad promo and brand to separate means
    summarise(mean_price = mean(price),mean_units = mean(units), value = (mean_price*mean_units)) %>% #create mean units and price, value = mean units * mean price
    
    count(brand,value,advert) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = brand, y = value, fill = advert)) + 
    geom_col(position = "dodge") +
    labs(x = "Brand Name", y = "Value Generated", title = "Advertisement is always better for General Mills", fill = "Advertisement Choice") +
  #Add labels to Brands for easier reading and prevention of overlapping
    scale_x_discrete(labels = c("CHEERIOS" = "Cheerios", "CINNAMON TST CR" = "Cinn. Toast", "COCOA PUFFS" = "Cocoa Puffs", "LUCKY CHARMS" = "Lucky Charms", "KIX" = "Kix"))
)
#Display Graph
AdValue

6.3.1 Comments

  • Possible that one advertisement option is propping up the other
    • But if we are looking for a net effect, its clear that Advertisement is better
  • Kix benefits the least, but still benefits from Advertisement
  • Cocoa Puffs gets the most value out of Advertisement

6.4 Which Ads are the most optimal for each brand?

#Read graph into BrandValue
BrandValue <- (
  fd2 %>% 
    filter(company == "GENERAL MILLS") %>% #filter to just general mills
    
    #mutate ad to say big ad for A, small ad for B, or No ad
    mutate(ad = ifelse(ad == "A", "Big Advertisement",
                         ifelse(ad == "B","Small Advertisement", "No Advertisement"))) %>% 
    
    
    group_by(ad,promo,brand) %>% #use ad promo and brand to separate means
    summarise(mean_price = mean(price),mean_units = mean(units), value = (mean_price*mean_units)) %>% #create mean units and price, create value variable
    ggplot(aes(x = brand, y = value, fill = ad)) + 
    geom_col(position = "dodge") +
    labs(x = "Brand Name", y = "Value Generated", title = "Atleast one form of advertisement is valuable across the board", fill = "Advertisement Choice") +
  #Add labels to Brands for easier reading and prevention of overlapping
    scale_x_discrete(labels = c("CHEERIOS" = "Cheerios", "CINNAMON TST CR" = "Cinn. Toast", "COCOA PUFFS" = "Cocoa Puffs", "LUCKY CHARMS" = "Lucky Charms", "KIX" = "Kix"))
)
#Display Graph
BrandValue

6.4.1 Comments

  • In every case, there is a form of advertisement that is better than no advertisement
  • Cheerios benefits from small advertisement, but loses value with big advertisements
  • Cinnamon Toast Crunch benefits from big advertisements, but loses value with small advertisements
  • Lucky Charms has an equal benefit from Small and Big Advertisements
    • Same with Kix and Cocoa Puffs

6.5 What Sales and Promotions is Kelloggs doing that is successful?

#Read Graph into KellogsValue
KelloggsValue <- (
  fd2 %>% 
    filter(company == "KELLOGGS") %>% #filter to just general mills
    
    mutate(promo = ifelse(promo == "0","No","Yes")) %>% #Change promo 0 into No and promo 1 into Yes
    #mutate ad to say big ad for A, small ad for B, or No ad
    mutate(ad = ifelse(ad == "A", "Big Advertisement",
                         ifelse(ad == "B","Small Advertisement", "No Advertisement"))) %>%
    
    group_by(ad,promo,brand) %>% #use ad promo and brand to separate means
    summarise(mean_price = mean(price),mean_units = mean(units), value = (mean_price*mean_units)) %>% #create mean units and price, create value variable
    ggplot(aes(x = ad, y = value, fill = promo)) + 
    geom_col(position = "dodge")) +
    labs(x = "Advertisement Option", y = "Value Generated", title = "Kelloggs generates value from all Promotions and all Advertisements", fill = "Promotion")
#Display Graph
KelloggsValue

6.5.1 Comments

  • Kelloggs benefits from all promotion in conjunction with every option

7 Statistical EDA

7.1 Promotions Improve Units Sold

7.1.1 Establish Hypothesis

Null: Promotions do not increase the amount of units sold Alternative: Promotions do increase the amount of units sold Level of Confidence: 0.05

7.1.2 Test Hypothesis

t.test(fd2$units[fd2$promo == "1"],fd2$units[fd2$promo == "0"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  fd2$units[fd2$promo == "1"] and fd2$units[fd2$promo == "0"]
## t = 27.59, df = 6398.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  3.070437 3.540125
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 11.196700  7.891419

7.1.3 Results

With our low p-value we can reject the null hypothesis as say that having a promotion over not having one does change the price at a 95% Confidence Interval.

7.2 Advertisements Improve Units Sold

7.2.1 Establish Hypothesis

Null: Advertisements do not increase the amount of units sold Alternative: Advertisements do increase the amount of units sold Level of Confidence: 0.05

7.2.2 Test Hypothesis

t.test(fd2$units[fd2$ad == "A" | fd2$ad == "B"],fd2$units[fd2$ad == "NONE"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  fd2$units[fd2$ad == "A" | fd2$ad == "B"] and fd2$units[fd2$ad == "NONE"]
## t = 17.093, df = 3032.3, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  2.372284 2.987070
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 10.949940  8.270263

7.2.3 Results

With our low p-value we can reject the null hypothesis as say that having a advertisement over not having one does change the price at a 95% Confidence Interval.

8 Main EDA Comments

  • While Promotion is not always in General Mills’ best interest to generate value, it is always in Kelloggs’ interest
  • General Mills brands all benefit from at least one form of advertisement over no advertisement
